audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design\codex-coherence-run.log:3235:audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design\critique-v2-dependence-sensitivity.md:33:The shipped engines demonstrate the inherited risk rather than solve it. E4-v4 takes a full `gamma x beta` grid and a full 54-point Cartesian box (`scripts/simulation/e4-v4-symmetric-frontier.mjs:55-64`) and reports the equally weighted fraction of box points favoring distributed (`scripts/simulation/e4-v4-symmetric-frontier.mjs:87-93`). E5 fixes `(p,beta,tau)` into two hand-built regimes (`scripts/simulation/e5-sp-symmetry-gate.mjs:116-117`), then gives equal weight to selected `lambda x rho x h` cells when pooling (`scripts/simulation/e5-sp-symmetry-gate.mjs:141-149`). Neither engine implements a dependence-aware joint law or an admissible-set analysis. Their pooled summaries are conditional on silent weighting measures and cannot validate v2's new method.
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design\codex-coherence-run.log:3236:audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design\critique-v2-dgp-registry-identification.md:39:- E5 also fixes a greedy (not optimal-knapsack) portfolio rule (`scripts/simulation/e5-sp-symmetry-gate.mjs:52-57`), rounds the central sample count and floors it at one (`scripts/simulation/e5-sp-symmetry-gate.mjs:77-85`), uses a z-score with a population denominator and an SD fallback of one (`scripts/simulation/e5-sp-symmetry-gate.mjs:24-27`), uses 100 worlds and fixed seeds (`scripts/simulation/e5-sp-symmetry-gate.mjs:102-108`), and evaluates two hand-fixed `(p,beta,tau)` regimes and small `lambda/rho/h` grids (`scripts/simulation/e5-sp-symmetry-gate.mjs:116-117`). Every one can move a finite-budget selection frontier.
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design\codex-coherence-run.log:3237:audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design\critique-v2-novelty-positioning.md:17:| An anchored simulation | Useful model criticism, **not methodological novelty**. It could be a substantive contribution only if it actually transports, implements, and validates the published moments. | Not shipped. The current symmetry gate uses an unbiased sampled central value estimate plus credit weight `lambda` (`scripts/simulation/e5-sp-symmetry-gate.mjs:77-90`) and sweeps `lambda`, `rho`, and `h`, not `a`, `b`, or `w` (`scripts/simulation/e5-sp-symmetry-gate.mjs:116-117,146-155`). |
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design\codex-coherence-run.log:3238:audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design\critique-v2-parity-boundary-analytic.md:151:That is a valid theorem for the old nested model, not for `a+bS+wZ`. In fact, a noiseless current central signal `bS` with `b>0` is equivalent to `η=1`: it ranks truth perfectly, so it weakly beats every `β>0` distributed signal and ties only at `β=0`. The old engine itself distinguishes the exact clean law from the noisy simulation: it declares the exact law at `scripts/simulation/e4-v4-symmetric-frontier.mjs:82-85`, while its reported full-simulation anti-diagonal includes `0.89` at `(η=1,β=0)` rather than parity (`research/e4-v4-symmetric-frontier-results.txt:8-17`).
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design\codex-coherence-run.log:3239:audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design\critique-v2-parity-objective-floor.md:53:The E5 gate uses the correct normalized per-world quantity, but it is a thresholded rebuild test, not the proposed anchored-central-arm parity surface (`scripts/simulation/e5-sp-symmetry-gate.mjs:102-117,140-166`). Reusing either output template would undo the stated objective.
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design\codex-coherence-run.log:3240:audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design\critique-v3-analytic-benchmark.md:124:The shipped engines do not fill this gap. The old E4 engine implements the retired two-harm-weight model and still prints the legacy exact-law sentence (`scripts/simulation/e4-v4-symmetric-frontier.mjs:36-50,82-85`). Its stochastic output has `D/C=0.89`, not parity, at `(gamma,beta)=(1,0)`, demonstrating that the clean law is already only a benchmark once sampling/noise are restored (`research/e4-v4-symmetric-frontier-results.txt:8-17`). The E5 gate implements MNAR reports but its central arm is an unbiased reach-times-sample-mean estimator plus credit, with no `a`, `b`, or `w` (`scripts/simulation/e5-sp-symmetry-gate.mjs:68-90`). Neither engine verifies (2)-(8) for v3.
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design\codex-coherence-run.log:3241:audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design\critique-v3-measure-free-sensitivity.md:125:axes, and pools selected cells with equal implicit weight (`scripts/simulation/e5-sp-symmetry-gate.mjs:116-117,141-149`).
audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design\codex-coherence-run.log:3242:audits/2026-07-11-v1.14-design\critique-v3-novelty-positioning.md:23:| [Böttcher & Klingebiel, “Organizational Selection of Innovation,” *Organization Science* 36(1), online 2024](https://doi.org/10.1287/orsc.2023.17357) ([author manuscript](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2405.09843)) | A budget permits selection of only `m` of `n` projects; projects have true quality and domain type; agents receive expertise-dependent noisy quality signals; the paper compares individual choice, project-expert delegation, approval voting, averaging, and rank aggregation on true selected-portfolio performance. It reports expert delegation winning when the relevant experts are available and identifiable, and aggregation generally winning otherwise, especially under tight selection. | Equal-cost/fixed-cardinality portfolios, unbiased expertise-dependent noise, and organizational agents—not E4's heterogeneous costs, citizen-valued target, sign-dependent MNAR participation, credit pressure, or source-to-target transport set. | This is the closest theoretical neighbor. Budgeted noisy portfolio selection and the conditional expert-versus-collective reversal are already published. E4 must show an incremental theorem generated by **biased transport plus coverage**, not claim the comparison or “either side can win” as novel. |
