defenses\D032-intertemporal-myopia-and-long-term-underinvestment.md:1:# D032 - Defense Against A032: Intertemporal Myopia and Long-Term Underinvestment
defenses\D032-intertemporal-myopia-and-long-term-underinvestment.md:9:- Attack file: [[A032-intertemporal-myopia-and-long-term-underinvestment|attacks/A032-intertemporal-myopia-and-long-term-underinvestment.md]]
defenses\D032-intertemporal-myopia-and-long-term-underinvestment.md:10:- Attack title: `A032 - Intertemporal Myopia and Long-Term Underinvestment`
defenses\D032-intertemporal-myopia-and-long-term-underinvestment.md:11:- Source: second-round attack queue, intertemporal myopia and long-term underinvestment.
defenses\D032-intertemporal-myopia-and-long-term-underinvestment.md:23:- Why it is not fatal to the architecture: the goods most vulnerable to myopia are shielded structurally rather than behaviorally, through the non-assignable pool, essential floors, and continuity-risk classification that generates continuity-need Ideas before funded periods expire.
defenses\D032-intertemporal-myopia-and-long-term-underinvestment.md:25:- Editorial distortion risk: medium. The attack distorts the project if it treats citizen myopia as strictly worse than the electoral myopia it replaces without evidence, since incumbent politicians also operate on a four-year horizon with less visibility of deferred maintenance.
defenses\D032-intertemporal-myopia-and-long-term-underinvestment.md:29:The defense is that the goods most vulnerable to myopia are protected by structure rather than trusted to citizen attention, while conceding that new long-horizon value above the floor faces real formation bias and that future citizens have no vote. The public budget boundary and essential floors remove catastrophic long-horizon obligations from monthly popularity, and the continuity project rule requires recurring, continuity-critical, and maintenance-dependent projects to expose the funded service period, renewal trigger, and wind-down rule. The continuity-risk classification exists precisely because attention cannot be trusted with these goods: it requires projects to declare whether they are one-time or maintenance-dependent, opens a continuity renewal window before the funded period ends, and surfaces the continuity need as an Idea before interruption rather than after failure. The monthly cycle itself carries the continuity label and can route eligible allocations toward follow-on, maintenance, and mitigation work instead of only toward new outputs.
defenses\README.md:86:| `D032` | `A032` | Intertemporal Myopia and Long-Term Underinvestment | Partially founded — resolved in [[100_LONG_HORIZON_LANES_AND_A032_RESOLUTION|docs/100_LONG_HORIZON_LANES_AND_A032_RESOLUTION.md]] |
attacks\A032-intertemporal-myopia-and-long-term-underinvestment.md:1:# A032 - Intertemporal Myopia and Long-Term Underinvestment
attacks\A032-intertemporal-myopia-and-long-term-underinvestment.md:41:- Keep monthly liquidity and bounded windows as the Core v0 default, and treat multi-cycle lanes, endowment funding, and horizon-weighted defaults as the Extension v1+ instruments that address formation-stage myopia.
attacks\A032-intertemporal-myopia-and-long-term-underinvestment.md:73:A commune runs the distributed model with strong participation for a decade. Every year, visible projects, courts, plazas, murals, and playgrounds, fund quickly and close on time. Maintenance of prior works, preventive infrastructure, and long-horizon resilience investments consistently fail to close their funding windows, because they cannot compete for monthly attention against gratifying new outputs. Administrators report a decade of high participation and completed projects, while the commune's built stock silently ages past its maintenance thresholds and its exposure to floods and slope failures grows. The eventual failures are attributed to bad luck, not to ten years of intertemporal myopia that the allocation mechanism quietly rewarded.
docs\37_SCOPE_CLASSIFICATION_MATRIX_V0.md:271:| Discount-correcting preferences and endowment lanes `A032` | Extension v1+ / planning-scope governance | Useful for countering myopia beyond defaults — discount-correcting citizen preferences, forced intergenerational weights, and multi-cycle or endowment lanes insulated from per-cycle attention — but a planning-scope political choice rather than a platform mandate and not required as a Core v0 object. Core v0 keeps the long-horizon lanes and intertemporal observability that carry planner-set horizon weights into defaults and make under-investment measurable; insulating long-horizon commitments from per-cycle attention remains Extension v1+. |
docs\38_V0_CONTRADICTION_AND_FAILURE_MODE_CHECKLIST.md:929:## A032 - Intertemporal myopia and long-term underinvestment
docs\38_V0_CONTRADICTION_AND_FAILURE_MODE_CHECKLIST.md:937:A032 is partially founded. Monthly allocation cycles reward visible near-term outputs and renewal windows re-expose long-horizon commitments to each cycle's shifting attention, so hyperbolic discounting tilts new funding away from maintenance, prevention, and intergenerational infrastructure, and future citizens are unrepresented in every funding attempt — but the goods most vulnerable to myopia are already shielded structurally, and the sharp edge is new long-horizon value above the floor. Under [[P007-integrate-or-bound-rule|knowledge/principles/P007-integrate-or-bound-rule.md]], this is a bounded resolution built on existing structures: formation-stage myopia threatens the aggregate-citizen-valuation claim and cannot be ignored, but the control fits existing objects — Planning Scopes, the non-assignable pool, continuity-risk classification (A006), and administrative observability — and the residual, an unrepresented future, is a declared limitation, not a mechanism Core v0 can supply.
attacks\README.md:75:| `A032` | Intertemporal Myopia and Long-Term Underinvestment | formation bias against long-horizon value (beyond A006 continuity) | resolved in `docs/100_LONG_HORIZON_LANES_AND_A032_RESOLUTION.md` |
