   1: # A Functional Architecture for Distributed Governance: Mechanism Design, Adversarial Stress-Testing, and a Symmetric Computational Test of Selective Institutional Distribution
   2: 
   3: **Working paper — v1.14 (July 2026; latest deposited version: v1.12, DOI 10.5281/zenodo.21252911). This version retires the earlier compound value-per-budget multiplier as a calibrated effect — a pre-registered symmetric selection-only stress test returned NO-GO (see §6 and the claim & estimand contract) — and rests on the architecture and the qualitative mechanism, now sharpened by a four-scenario robustness map (E4 v1.14) that reconciles the conservative gate — its near-parity no-myopia regime — with a realistic case in which the central is myopic to harm on the low-visibility long tail and coverage-routed selection pulls ahead; all such magnitudes are declared reference points, not calibrated impact. Revised through successive adversarial and author review cycles, documented in the repository's roadmap. It consolidates the companion computational program (Offermann 2026b): the deterrence-complementarity rule, the semi-open transition path, the budget-release rule, and machine verification with the human second instance; and the companion's two-layer separation of the macro categorization from the allocation profiles, under which the distributed arm is robust to a bad central categorization while the central arm is fragile to it.**
   4: 
   5: *© 2026 Mauricio Offermann. Licensed CC BY 4.0 — see LICENSE.md at the repository root. Please cite as indicated in CITATION.cff. DOI (concept, always resolves to the latest version): 10.5281/zenodo.21193846.*
   6: 
   7: ## Abstract
   8: 
   9: Public resources are allocated and controlled by institutions that fuse three functions — who selects projects, who executes them, and who judges whether they delivered. That fusion is where waste, capture, and unaccountable failure concentrate. This paper asks whether a bounded share of that machinery can separate those functions — and the information that drives them — while preserving legal authorization and public auditability.
  10: 
  11: We present **Core v0**, a fully specified, object-level architecture. Within legally authorized planning scopes, citizens direct a non-withdrawable share of an existing public budget to projects that must declare value claims, affected parties, milestones, and evidence contracts up front. Proposing, execution, evidence production, fiscalization, and custody are separated; funds move in tranches against reviewed milestone evidence, with retention and guarantees; executors neither choose nor pay their inspectors; and every consequential state transition is public.
  12: 
  13: Its animating idea is a **credit-versus-coverage** mechanism: when central ranking rewards claimable political credit, it can systematically underweight the diffuse, low-visibility benefits that a coverage-based distributed process still surfaces, albeit under voice bias. We held this idea to a deliberately hostile test — a pre-registered, symmetric simulation that stripped out the favorable asymmetries an earlier version had relied on, plus a public adversarial review of 43 attacks across five rounds, each integrated into the design or recorded as a bounded limitation. The distributed advantage was positive in all 18 pre-specified cells but small (pooled median Δ = 0.025 of a full-information greedy benchmark, below our pre-set 0.05 threshold); we therefore retire the large multiplier an earlier version reported and state the modest, conditional result plainly. A four-scenario robustness extension then maps where each institution wins: a competent, harm-aware central ties (the pre-registered near-parity regime), while a central realistically myopic to harm on the low-visibility long tail loses to coverage — a reconciliation, not a contradiction, of the conservative gate, with all magnitudes reported as source-motivated declared reference points rather than calibrated impact. Elementary propositions give sufficient conditions for incentive-compatible disbursement and collusion-proof fiscalization under independence and corroboration assumptions.
  14: 
  15: This is an architecture-and-mechanism contribution, not an impact evaluation: no pilot has run; the simulation's units are uncalibrated and partial-equilibrium and do not identify delivery effects; and claims are scoped to infrastructure-like public investment. What it offers is a concrete, criticizable, pilotable institutional design — and a disciplined account of exactly what its evidence does and does not yet support.
  16: 
  17: ## 1. Introduction
  18: 
  19: Modern states concentrate three things that need not sit together: the
  20: authority to decide what public money is spent on, the capacity to execute
  21: that spending, and the power to certify that it achieved anything. When all
  22: three live inside one hierarchy, accountability comes down to it auditing
  23: itself (Bovens 2007). The consequences are predictable and documented across
  24: political economy — discretionary allocation, self-reported compliance,
  25: capture by concentrated interests, and citizen distrust — from regulatory
  26: capture (Stigler 1971; Laffont and Tirole 1991) to audit turned ritual (Power
  27: 1997) to the distributional coalitions that entrench themselves in stable
  28: political systems (Olson 1982).
  29: 
  30: These failures are not abstract: they are why the value never reaches the
  31: people it was raised for. For the public money that funds concrete projects —
  32: infrastructure, works, local programs — what ultimately matters is not how much
  33: is appropriated but how much effective value reaches people per unit spent: a
  34: project that is never built, or built badly, helps no one, however
  35: well-intentioned the allocation (Okun's (1975) leaky bucket carried water that
  36: never arrived). This is a bounded criterion for project-type public investment,
  37: not a theory of the whole budget or of why states tax: redistribution and equity
  38: are distinct purposes of public finance that this paper does not evaluate (§8).
  39: 
  40: The standard debate responds with quantity: shrink the state or grow it. Both
  41: positions treat it as a single object. This paper argues the tractable
  42: question is architectural, not one of size: *which layers of state activity
  43: still require central monopoly, and which can now be distributed — with better
  44: accountability than the status quo — now that digital coordination has
  45: collapsed the transaction costs that once justified hierarchy?* (Coase 1937;
  46: Hayek 1945; Williamson 1985). It is a question with a lineage — where
  47: decisions should sit when knowledge is dispersed — from the economic
  48: calculation debate (Mises 1920) to Hayek's dispersed knowledge and its
  49: institutional treatment in Sowell (1980): decisions should live where the
  50: knowledge is, disciplined by feedback rather than top-down command. Rights
  51: guarantees, legitimate force, macro-fiscal stability, and enforceable
  52: adjudication plausibly remain central; information processing, project-level
  53: resource allocation, service execution, evidence production, and auditing
  54: plausibly do not.
  55: 
  56: We make the argument as a concrete design, not a manifesto. Core v0 is a
  57: complete reference architecture for distributing one bounded layer — the
  58: allocation, execution, and verification of a legally mandated share of an
  59: existing public budget — developed to the level of named objects, state
  60: machines, and decision rules (a corpus of more than one hundred architecture
  61: documents, fifty-nine designed hypotheses, and forty-three adversarial reviews, all
  62: public). Citizens receive periodic, non-withdrawable allocation capacity in a
  63: civic wallet; projects pass through a parallel-closure lifecycle in which
  64: funding, independent fiscalization, evidence commitments, and beneficiary
  65: confirmation must all close before execution; the executor never selects or
  66: pays its own auditors — which removes the agency cost of self-monitored
  67: compliance (Jensen and Meckling 1976); money moves only on reviewed
  68: milestones, with retention and externally materialized guarantees; and every
  69: consequential state transition is recorded in a citizen-legible,
  70: expert-auditable trail.
  71: 
  72: The *executor* —whoever carries out the project, be it a public work, a
  73: personal-care service, or an educational program— can be a public agency, a
  74: municipality, a foundation, a cooperative, or a firm, as the implementing
  75: authority's rules define, under one condition: non-monopolistic, honest
  76: competition, with bankruptcies and consequences for whoever fails to deliver.
  77: And the share each citizen directs is set by a public, versioned formula the
  78: authority chooses; its simple option is *equal for all eligible citizens*,
  79: under which no one buys more influence with more money.
  80: 
  81: A concrete example. Suppose a municipality funds care programs for vulnerable
  82: elderly people. Today, between the peso allocated and the help that actually
  83: arrives lies a gap where value is lost. Under this architecture, each resident
  84: can direct part of their taxes to the program they prefer; the foundation,
  85: cooperative, or service that carries it out is paid in tranches, and only once
  86: a verifier it did not choose confirms the help arrived; and every step is
  87: public and auditable.
  88: 
  89: What makes a design exercise count as research is the rigor it is put through,
  90: under one transversal discipline: every claim is evaluated against how the
  91: current institution solves the same problem, not against an ideal — blocking the nirvana fallacy —comparing the real institution against an unattainable ideal rather than the available alternative— in both directions (Section 2). Our contributions are:
  92: 
  93: 1. **Distributing the allocation layer.** The core design contribution:
  94:    applying the functional-distribution principle to resource allocation —
  95:    citizens direct their share directly, delegate it, or govern it with
  96:    personal rules — instantiated as a complete reference architecture (Core
  97:    v0).
  98: 
  99: 2. **Formalization of the incentive mechanisms** (Section 5). We model
 100:    milestone-gated disbursement as a principal-agent game and derive its
 101:    incentive-compatibility condition; we model bribery of protocol-assigned
 102:    fiscalizers and derive a collusion-proofness condition under
 103:    k-corroboration; and we prove two design-relevant comparative statics: weak
 104:    verification must be compensated with financial terms, and guarantees are
 105:    counterproductive when detection quality falls below the cost of capital.
 106:    Milestones, retention, guarantees, and reputational memory form the
 107:    design's deterrence stack.
 108: 
 109: 3. **Computational evidence** (Section 6). A dependency-free, seeded
 110:    agent-based simulation of 10,000 citizens tests the architecture's
 111:    behavioral assumptions under rational ignorance, limited discovery
 112:    attention, and social-proof cascades. The results discipline the design:
 113:    they support some claims, sharpen others, quantify the leverage
 114:    concentrated in the scope-construction layer, measure a viable open
 115:    construction of it, and carry the comparison end to end: from allocation to
 116:    delivered social value per unit of budget — one relevant criterion for this
 117:    bounded slice of public spending (alongside distributional and rights
 118:    constraints the model does not represent). In the model, verified delivery and social prioritization
 119:    interact rather than merely add; the earlier agent-based apparatus produced a
 120:    compound of 2.22× a status-quo baseline parameterized from published
 121:    audit-institution findings (1.4–1.6× at municipal pilot scale). We **retire
 122:    that compound as a calibrated effect**: a pre-registered, symmetric,
 123:    selection-only stress test shrinks the distributed-minus-central selection
 124:    advantage to a pre-registered pooled median Δ = 0.025 of a full-information
 125:    benchmark, below its pre-set 0.05 research-program rebuild gate (NO-GO). The
 126:    load-bearing contribution is the architecture and the qualitative mechanism,
 127:    whose comparative scope the v1.14 robustness map delimits across the no-myopia
 128:    and harm-myopia regimes—not the multiplier.
 129: 
 130: 4. **Adversarial review as method** (Section 7). The architecture was attacked
 131:    systematically: forty-three attack briefs grounded in the political-science,
 132:    economics, and law literatures, each answered by a paired defense and
 133:    resolved under an explicit integrate-or-bound rule, with resolutions
 134:    propagated through the corpus (all except the manuscript-review round's
 135:    D037–D040, whose corpus propagation is tracked) and the full review
 136:    record public by construction. The loop is a structured self-critique, not external
 137:    validation, and we say so; we propose it, and its terminating rule—pending independent external validation—as a preliminary methodological proposal for institutional design research.
 138: 
 139: A companion study measures three effects that extend this architecture:
 140: ablation of the deterrence stack (its terms are individually redundant but
 141: jointly indispensable), the feasibility of AI-based fiscalization, and the
 142: effect of separating macro planning from allocation (robustness to poor
 143: central planning — an earlier-apparatus contrast, subject to the same
 144: magnitude caveat as the compound above, not a calibrated effect).
 145: 
 500: projects is negligible, so rational ignorance is the equilibrium (Downs
 501: 1957), and the design question is where the *inattentive* majority's weight
 502: flows: to salience amplified by social proof (Bikhchandani, Hirshleifer and
 503: Welch 1992; Salganik, Dodds and Watts 2006), or to the architecture's own
 504: default layer, whose routing follows the distributed project prioritization
 505: — the aggregated allocation profiles — not a central plan. The model yields three testable
 506: predictions — caps tame cascades (prediction 1), defaults anchor quality (prediction 2), decay
 507: degrades gracefully only with defaults (prediction 3) — evaluated next.
 508: 
 509: ## 6. Computational evidence
 510: 
 511: We test the three predictions of §5.3 —and, in successive experiments, the
 512: assumptions of Propositions 1–4— in an agent-based simulation. Each experiment
 513: (E1–E8) corresponds to a finding:
 514: 
 515: | Exp | What it tests | |
 516: |---|---|---|
 517: | E1 | do funding caps raise quality? | Finding 1 |
 518: | E2 | what carries allocation quality? | Finding 2 |
 519: | E3 | what buffers participation decay? | Finding 3 |
 520: | E4 | distributed aggregation vs. central construction (refined by a symmetric-frictions frontier + capture, E4-v4/v5; and a v1.14 harm-myopia four-scenario robustness map, §6) | Finding 4 |
 521: | E5 | where the architecture gains value (selection and delivery layers) | Finding 5 |
 522: | E6 | reputational competition and execution standard | Finding 6 |
 523: | E7 | comparison against an audit-parameterized baseline | Finding 7 |
 524: | E8 | robustness under endogenous behavioral participation | close of §6 |
 525: 
 526: We simulate 10,000 citizens over 24 monthly cycles allocating across a
 527: standing pool of 40 projects with quality *θ*, salience *s* (measured
 528: corr(*θ*, *s*) ≈ 0.24), prioritization need-weights *w* = λ*θ* + (1 − λ)*u*
 529: (where *u* is an idiosyncratic need component independent of quality) with
 530: mixing weight λ ∈ {0.4, 0.8} — measured corr(*θ*, *w*) ≈ 0.55 and ≈ 0.97
 531: respectively — and 3× scarcity (only a minority of projects can
 532: complete). Evaluators (2–10%) fund the best quality they sample; salience
 533: followers see a six-slot discovery surface ranked by salience amplified by
 534: funding progress; default followers' budget fills projects in planning-
 535: priority order. The funding-target closure rule is toggleable. Twenty
 536: seeded runs per condition; the code is dependency-free and deterministic
 537: (`scripts/simulation/allocation-sim.mjs`; full tables in
 538: [simulation-results](../research/simulation-results.md)).
 539: 
 540: **Status of the earlier compound ratios.** Three baselines of the same
 541: value-per-budget ratio were produced by this agent-based apparatus: **2.19×**
 542: against zero-control (E5), **2.22×** against the audit-parameterized status quo
 543: (E7), and **2.26×** under behavioral adoption (E8). They are retained here for
 544: traceability as **conditional outputs of that apparatus**, but are **superseded
 545: for magnitude inference** and are no longer offered as the paper's headline.
 546: 
 547: **Quantitative status (governing).** A pre-registered, symmetric, selection-only
 548: stress test — both arms with matched expected appraisal-report budgets, the same
 549: candidate pool, costs and noise, delivery at parity, each acting on its own noisy
 550: estimate rather than ground truth — found the distributed-minus-central selection
 551: advantage **positive in every one of 18 pre-specified cells but small.** The
 552: pre-registered decision statistic is the **pooled median Δ = 0.025**, below the
 553: pre-registered **0.05 research-program rebuild gate**; a **post-hoc** ratio-of-sums estimate is
 554: **Δ = 0.026, with a 95% world-cluster Monte-Carlo interval [0.023, 0.029]**
 555: (reported separately, on the simulated data-generating process). The compound
 556: multiplier is therefore **not** claimed as a calibrated effect. This is a stylized
 557: test of a *selection mechanism*, not a validated implementation of Core v0: its
 558: value and credit variables are abstract scores, not measured visibility,
 559: traceability, permanence, or public value. The **0.05** figure is a
 560: research-program **rebuild threshold** on this uncalibrated scale (a go/no-go rule
 561: for whether to pursue a quantitative rebuild), **not** a calibrated policy-materiality
 562: threshold. The controlling specification is
 563: [claim-and-estimand-contract](../research/claim-and-estimand-contract.md); the test,
 564: its frozen pre-registration, results, and diagnostics are
 565: `scripts/simulation/e5-sp-symmetry-gate.mjs` and `audits/2026-07-10/symmetry-gate-*`.
 566: The load-bearing contributions are the architecture, the mechanism direction, and
 567: the v1.14 comparative robustness map across declared no-myopia and harm-myopia
 568: regimes—not a point multiplier or calibrated impact.
 569: 
 570: **The symmetric credit-versus-coverage gate (methods and result).** Because this
 571: is the paper's one confirmatory computation, its design is stated in full here
 572: rather than only by reference. Each world holds K = 500 candidate projects; for
 573: each, N = 5000 potential participants are considered, each interested with a
 574: project-specific probability, so the interested reach is at most N and endogenous.
 575: Both arms then see the
 576: same candidate pool, the same exact costs, the same truth net[j] = S[j] − h·cost[j],
 577: delivery held at **parity**, and the same report noise report = v + Normal(0, τ);
 578: each funds a **greedy** set under a budget of one-third of total project cost, is
 579: eligible to fund a project only where *its own* noisy estimate of net is positive
 580: (no oracle gate), and its delivered value is scored on the projects' *true* net.
 581: The arms are symmetric except for the coverage mechanism and its matched
 582: counterparts. *Distributed (endogenous coverage):* each interested citizen reports
 583: independently with probability p if her value v ≥ 0 and p·(1 − β) if v < 0 (adverse
 584: voice bias), giving ĥS_D = Σreports / p, ranked by estimated net per cost.
 585: *Central (competent value-reader):* an appraisal budget matched to the distributed
 586: arm's *expected* total reports in that world, spread **evenly** across projects as a
 587: rounded fixed per-project bandwidth m_C = round(expected reports / K) (so the two
 588: arms' appraisal totals are equal in expectation up to that rounding); per project it
 589: samples m_C interested citizens, observes v + Normal(0, τ), and forms its own noisy
 590: ĥNet_C = reach·mean(observed) − h·cost. It ranks by score = (1 − λ)·z(ĥNet_C/cost) + λ·z(P/cost) — its **own noisy
 591: estimate**, never the true net — where P is claimable political credit (the
 592: electoral credit-claiming and traceability logic by which visible, attributable
 593: benefits are favoured over diffuse ones; Mayhew 1974; Arnold 1990) and λ is bounded
 594: credit pressure (a *posited* pressure whose real-world magnitude must be measured,
 595: not assumed). Credit moves *ranking*, never eligibility (no knowingly
 596: value-destroying planner). The legitimate asymmetries are therefore only these:
 597: distributed reports self-route to projects citizens care about while negative
 598: stakeholders participate less, and central appraisal is spread evenly while its
 599: ranking carries credit pressure — everything else is shared. The estimand is
 600: **Δ = (D − C)/O** per world, where D, C, O are delivered true net for the
 601: distributed, central, and full-information greedy arms and O is a reference level,
 602: not an optimum. The frozen grid sweeps λ ∈ {0, 0.1, 0.2, 0.3} (λ = 0 a negative
 603: control), a latent-correlation setting ρ ∈ {0, 0.5, 1} (realized corr(S, P) ≈ 0.00,
 604: 0.30, 0.82), and h ∈ {1.5, 2.5, 4} over 100 seeded worlds, in a baseline
 605: observation regime (p = .35, β = .30, τ = .5) and a matched-budget low-information
 606: stress regime (p = .15, β = .60, τ = 1.0). The **pre-registered decision rule** —
 607: frozen before running and designed by the independent auditor to be adversarial —
 608: required, for a GO on rebuilding the quantitative engine, at least 15 of the 18
 609: primary cells with mean Δ > 0, a pooled **median Δ ≥ 0.05**, a bootstrap lower
 610: bound > 0, and median Δ ≥ 0 under the stress regime, plus a guard to pause if the
 611: λ = 0 control itself exceeded 0.05. The result was **NO-GO**: the advantage was
 612: positive in all 18 primary cells, but the pre-registered pooled **median Δ = 0.025**,
 613: below the 0.05 rebuild gate; the λ = 0 negative control sat at ≈ 0.016, within the
 614: pause guard (no hidden asymmetry flagged). A **post-hoc** world-cluster
 615: ratio-of-sums estimate was Δ = 0.026 [0.023, 0.029] (Monte-Carlo uncertainty on the
 616: simulated data-generating process, reported separately from the median). The
 617: advantage rises with credit pressure λ and falls as credit aligns with value — the
 618: credit-versus-coverage mechanism — but it is small, which is why the calibrated
 619: multiplier is retired and the paper rests on the architecture and the mechanism
 620: direction, now sharpened by the robustness map below.
 621: 
 622: **A realistic-myopia extension (v1.14): a four-scenario robustness map.** The
 623: pre-registered gate above equips the central arm with competent, *harm-aware*
 624: appraisal. A v1.14 extension asks what happens when the central is realistically
 625: **myopic to harm on the low-visibility long tail** — where routine oversight,
 626: opposition and audit attention reach mainly the visible, contested few. It splits
 627: true value into support and harm, S = S⁺ − H, and gives the central a
 628: salience-gated harm term, M_C = a + b·S⁺ + w·(v_p − S⁺) − b_H·s(V)·H + η, whose
 629: harm-detection s(V) rises with a project's visibility; the distributed arm registers
 630: harm across the whole distribution. Holding the budget matched and scoring delivery
 631: on true value, four declared scenarios (plus one diagnostic contrast) level the field
 632: for both institutions, reported as the signed fraction of the full-information greedy
 633: benchmark, parity at zero (`npm run e4:scenarios`). At the **central's declared
 634: full-favourable endpoint** — low participation and a competent, harm-aware central —
 635: the *central wins*, delivering ≈ 98% of the benchmark against ≈ 68% for the
 636: distributed arm. Under the **probable** reference the distributed arm delivers ≈ 91%
 637: and the central ≈ 45%. At the **distributed-favourable** case the myopic central
 638: funds net-harmful projects and delivers *negative* value while the distributed arm
 639: delivers ≈ 96%. A diagnostic contrast that turns off harm-myopia *alone* (only the
 640: two harm-gate coordinates) accounts for about 40% of the sequential move from the
 641: probable gap; the further move to a fully harm-aware, competent **no-myopia bundle**
 642: returns the arms to near-parity — the same regime as the pre-registered gate's
 643: Δ ≈ 0.025, which by construction equipped the central with harm-aware appraisal. The
 644: two results are therefore the same phenomenon under opposite assumptions, not a
 645: contradiction: assume the central sees harm and the advantage collapses to the gate's
 646: near-parity; let it be realistically myopic and the coverage arm pulls ahead. A
 647: stylized joint-normal fixed-threshold benchmark (`research/e4-parity-theorem.md`)
 648: places the parity boundary at the equality of the two selectors' signal-to-noise
 649: covariance ratios, and a ceteris-paribus path from the probable to the
 650: central-favourable scenario crosses parity partway along the declared segment. These
 651: magnitudes are **source-motivated declared reference and stress points, not
 652: target-domain calibrated bands** (the intervals cover inner Monte-Carlo variability
 653: only, and the harm-myopia strength is the load-bearing, least-empirically-pinned
 654: assumption); the honest object is where each institution wins and how much the answer
 655: depends on that assumption, not a single number. Administrative-cost savings and
 656: corruption/leakage are separate, additive channels, deliberately excluded here.
 657: 
 658: **Finding 1: funding caps are an anti-concentration device, not a quality
 659: device.** With closure ON, concentration falls (funding Gini 0.732 vs
 660: 0.759), the most salient 5% of projects absorb less (16.8% vs 19.6% of all
 661: funding), and 15% more projects complete (25.3% vs 21.9%). But quality
 662: selection is unchanged (*sel(θ)*, the Pearson correlation across projects between
 663: latent quality θ and the binary indicator that a project reaches its funding
 664: target, ≈ 0.39 vs 0.41): the truncated surplus
 665: spills to the next most *visible* project, not the next *best* one. The
 666: architecture's claim for the closure rule should be — and in the corpus now
 667: is — bounded accordingly.
 668: 
 669: **Finding 2: the default anchor, not citizen attention, carries allocation
 670: quality.** A default-anchored mix, with a near-perfectly informed planner (r ≈
 671: 0.97), reaches sel(θ) ≈ 0.71: between 1.6× and 2× the salience-driven
 672: configurations (≈ 0.35–0.43). Quintupling citizen attention (α from 2% to
 673: 10%), by contrast, barely moves the needle —at most ≈ 0.08 in salience-driven
 674: regimes, and essentially nothing in default-anchored ones—, while degrading
 675: the vector's informational quality from near-perfect to moderate (r ≈ 0.97 →
 676: 0.55) costs ≈ 0.29 of selection. The anchor rules, not attention.
 677: 
 678: Two qualifications keep the finding honest:
 679: 
 680: - **By construction.** The default rule is a deterministic θ-correlated
 681:   allocator already holding most of the budget; what is measured is the
 682:   *conditioning* —how much the vector's informational quality determines the
 683:   anchor's value, and how little attention substitutes for it—, not the wisdom
 684:   of the crowd.
 685: 
 686: - **Robustness.** A sensitivity panel (varying evaluator sample size and
 687:   social-proof strength) shows the regime ordering is robust, except under
 688:   very strong social proof, where the regimes converge within noise because
 689:   strong amplification also propagates the evaluators' quality signal.
 690:   Magnitudes are parameter-dependent and uncalibrated; what survives all
 691:   variations is the ordering and the dominance of the prioritization's
 692:   informational quality.
 693: 
 694: This finding quantifies the leverage concentrated in whatever constructs the
 695: project prioritization the passive share follows. That prioritization has two
 696: layers —which a companion study (Offermann 2026b) separated for the first
 697: time—: the macro categorization (this corpus's Planning Scope, which frames
 698: eligibility and carries no budget weights) and the aggregated allocation
 699: profiles that route budget within it. The distributed arm is robust to the
 700: quality of that categorization and a central arm is fragile to it, so the
 701: advantage over a central status quo is not fixed: it grows as central planning
 702: worsens — a model-internal direction the companion apparatus illustrates (a
 703: conditional contrast rising from roughly twofold to more than fivefold, not a
 704: calibrated multiplier; see the quantitative-status note in this section).
 705: 
 706: Two architectural facts scope the statement and forestall a tempting
 707: over-reading. First, the default layer is pluggable, not mandatorily central:
 708: the civic autopilot gives each citizen manual allocation, delegation,
 709: published allocation profiles, a personal automatic rule, or the system
 710: default; an onboarding citizen must explicitly select or acknowledge a base
 711: profile, and only the share who never engage necessarily follows the system
 712: default —which itself operates under a recorded allocation mandate. Second,
 713: centralized construction of scope weights is a property of the closed and
 714: tutored transition modes, not of the architecture: operating modes are
 715: country-configured states, and the designed trajectory is toward open
 716: construction (Finding 4 measures its in-model viability).
 717: 
 718: The numbers therefore establish a conditional. The binding constraint on
 719: allocation quality is the informational quality of the **project
 720: prioritization the passive share follows** —the aggregated allocation
1065: the baseline's leak, it does not calibrate the institutional treatment effect. And the bias
1066: sweep bounds the open-construction claim honestly: distributed
1067: selection degrades near-linearly with coordinated signal capture and
1068: crosses below a competent full-coverage municipal planner only at
1069: roughly a thirty percent coordinated share — it degrades, never
1070: collapses, and remains superior everywhere below ten percent.
1071: 
1072: A pre-registered eighth experiment (E8,
1073: `research/e8-behavioral-participation-design.md`) then replaced the
1074: participation side of these arms — the default share and informed share
1075: the architecture arms had imposed — with adoption trajectories generated
1076: by a companion behavioral study: a Core v0-conformant agent-based model
1077: of awareness, registration, participation modes, and trusted
1078: microdelegation, calibrated with LLM-elicited synthetic priors
1079: (replication package: the distributed-governance-experiments
1080: repository). The earlier apparatus produced 2.26 [2.23, 2.30] at scale under its
1081: synthetic adoption assumptions and 2.15–2.9× across three populations and all
1082: scales, including a launch trajectory that begins near zero
1083: participation — which costs 1.7% of the ratio, because the default layer
1084: anchors the thin early cycles by construction. The behavioral study also
1085: independently reproduces the informed-share assumption these experiments
1086: had imposed: 0.309 emergent against the 0.30 assumed.
1087: 
1088: **What survives.** Stripped to what the governing test supports: (1) under the
1089: pre-registered symmetric gate the distributed selection advantage is *positive but
1090: small* (median Δ = 0.025, below the 0.05 rebuild gate; NO-GO); (1b) a v1.14
1091: four-scenario robustness extension maps where each institution wins once the central
1092: can be realistically *myopic to harm on the low-visibility long tail*: a competent,
1093: harm-aware central ties (the gate's no-myopia regime), while a myopic central loses
1094: to coverage — the same phenomenon under opposite assumptions, with all magnitudes
1095: reported as declared reference and stress points, not calibrated impact; (2) the
1096: load-bearing contributions are the architecture and the qualitative
1097: credit-versus-coverage mechanism — credit-pressured central ranking underweights
1098: diffuse value that coverage-based distributed selection surfaces; (3) every compound
1099: ratio above
1100: (2.19×/2.22×/2.26×, +43%, +53–54%, ~2×–5×) is a conditional, model-internal
1101: apparatus output, not a calibrated effect; and (4) any calibrated total delivered-
1102: value effect — selection *and* delivery, on real data — remains future work.
1103: 
1104: ## 7. Adversarial review as method
1105: 
1106: The architecture was developed under a documented adversarial loop:
1107: **attack** (a brief stating a failure mode, its location in the corpus, a
1108: stress scenario, and literature anchors) → **paired defense** (an objective
1109: evaluation classifying the attack as founded, partially founded, or a
1110: difference of judgment, with line-anchored citations into the corpus) →
1360: increments.
1361: 
1362: The same experiments measured a variable this corpus had left unregulated:
1363: *when* the authority releases budget into the allocation machinery. The
1364: resulting deployment rule: meter release against a work-in-progress ceiling
1365: calibrated to the delivery-and-verification pipeline's throughput and cycle
1366: time — never against the calendar. Calendar release freezes months of
1367: budget in escrow and saturates verification; and when verification capacity
1368: is scarce, no release policy compensates — verification capacity is the
1369: pipeline's ceiling before it is the anti-fraud instrument. The rule is
1370: conditional on a carryforward instrument (the semi-open envelope is
1371: precisely such a vehicle); under strict budget annuality it degenerates to
1372: within-year metering.
1373: 
1374: Finally, the technological premise that lowers participation costs on the
1375: citizen side (the AI tutor) applies symmetrically to the control side.
1376: Machine verification of protocolizable evidence classes multiplies
1377: fiscalization capacity, with humans as the permanent second instance —
1378: sampled re-verification with a published floor, seeded known-answer
1379: controls as the calibration and drift-detection instrument, auditing the
1380: verifier rather than competing with it — so that the machine's error rate
1381: remains measured and the human control profession remains funded from the
1382: control budget it relieves. Measured on a five-family panel of real models
1383: (Offermann 2026b), frontier models converge on good specificity and fraud
1384: detection on document-legible evidence while small local models are weaker,
1385: and evidence contracts that include objective comparison references (market
1386: benchmarks, duration bands, thresholds) let a strict verifier judge rather
1387: than guess. The machine layer reaches only document-legible, delivery-phase
1388: fraud — physical quality-below-spec and pre-contract theft remain fully
1389: human, so provenance attestation is tamper-evidence at capture, not
1390: court-grade proof, and evidentiary admissibility still needs custody, contradiction,
1391: and expert testimony. Contraposed citizen evidence — independent producers
1392: with interests opposed to the executor, whose anticipated existence deters
1393: diversion — keeps the watching distributed even as routine
1394: document-verification labor shrinks; but its strength equals the
1395: *independence* of the contributor layer, and a colluding ring that captures
1396: or silences it erases the effect. Cross-layer collusion is in fact the one
1397: adversary that bypasses the per-milestone deterrence and moves leakage by an
1398: order of magnitude (while the delivered-value advantage survives), so
1399: collusion resistance — verified beneficial ownership, contributor
1400: Sybil-resistance, and decentralization of the assigner and the audit-budget
1401: floor — is a first-class requirement ([docs/113](../docs/113_VERIFICATION_PACKAGE_AND_A043_RESOLUTION.md)), not a residual caution.
1402: 
1403: ## 10. Conclusion
1404: 
1405: For the bounded public-investment allocation problem studied here, a
1406: relevant criterion is not how faithfully an institution executes a plan
1407: but how much delivered, verified value it produces per unit of public
1408: resource (Musgrave 1959; Okun 1975) — one criterion alongside the
1409: distributional and rights constraints this model does not represent. This
1410: paper's contribution is an architecture that makes that criterion
1411: operational — and a disciplined account of exactly how far its evidence
1412: reaches. The
1413: architecture's spine is two separable questions anyone can ask. First:
1414: take the same projects, designed identically, and change only who
1415: executes and how they are watched — does the visibly audited regime with
1416: reputational consequences deliver more than the one without them? Second:
1417: hold the control layer fixed and change only which projects get funded,
1418: centrally planned or socially prioritized? In the exploratory simulation
1419: apparatus the answer to both is yes — a verified-delivery gain and a
1420: selection gain that interact rather than merely add — but those
1421: magnitudes are model-internal factorial contrasts, not calibrated
1422: effects, and we do not build the paper on them. The claim the paper
1423: actually stands on is narrower and was tested harder: a pre-registered,
1424: symmetric, selection-only gate finds the distributed-minus-central
1425: advantage positive in every cell but small (a pre-registered pooled median
1426: Δ = 0.025 of a full-information benchmark, below its pre-set 0.05
1427: research-program rebuild gate). The v1.14 robustness map treats that result as the
1428: near-parity no-myopia anchor and maps where each institution wins across declared
1429: harm-myopia scenarios, including a central-favourable endpoint. We therefore retire
1430: the compound multiplier an earlier version reported and rest on the architecture,
1431: the qualitative mechanism, and this conditional comparative map; its magnitudes are
1432: declared reference and stress points, not calibrated impact. One model-internal result is worth carrying because it is
1433: about the delivery layer, not the multiplier: in the model, at E7's
1434: audit-informed (but not yet fully source-verified) detection intensity,
1435: detection without persistent consequences deters no diversion; what moves delivered value is the
1436: instrument the modelled status quo lacks — consequences that persist. Whether
1437: that holds in a real institution is a hypothesis for a pilot, not a result
1438: here; but the model is unambiguous that accountability without memory is
1439: bookkeeping.
1440: 
1441: The deeper point is Friedman's: a central administration spends other
1442: people's money on other people, the spending category with the least care
1443: for both cost and value (Friedman and Friedman 1980). This architecture
1444: does not answer that problem with exhortation; it re-plumbs the bucket.
1445: Planning remains — as the guiding thread that sets scopes, floors, and
1446: mandates — but the engine of value is the conversion layer: measurable
1447: promises, conditional release, independent verification, consequences that
1448: compound into reputation, and a meter on every leak. The question this
1449: paper answers is therefore not whether states should be bigger or smaller,
1450: but whether the layers of state activity that fail through information and
1451: incentive monopoly can be re-architected to fail less — and to show their
1452: failures when they do. For one such layer we have specified a complete
1453: architecture, proved the incentive conditions its mechanisms depend on,
1454: measured selection, aggregation, and delivery in simulation against a
1455: baseline the incumbent system's own auditors supplied, and subjected
1456: the whole to five rounds of documented adversarial review with an
1457: explicit integrate-or-bound discipline. The result is deliberately modest
1458: in its claims and unusually explicit about their edges: allocation quality
1459: rides on the informational quality of whatever constructs the weight
1460: vector, whose open construction is measured viable but whose honest
1461: elicitation remains the open problem; delivered value rides on
1462: verification whose market conditions must be priced; legitimacy rides on
1463: mandates the platform can record but not create. What distinguishes the
1464: proposal is that these edges are specified, monitored, and attached to
1465: named objects — which is, we argue, what it looks like when institutional
1466: design is treated as an engineering discipline rather than an ideological
1467: one.
1468: 
1469: ## Appendix: E4 calibration targets
1470: 
1471: The E4-v4/v5 magnitudes are model-internal; the table names, for each parameter, the
1472: real dataset that *could* inform it — making the boundary between model-internal and
1473: empirically-anchored a visible line rather than a caveat buried in prose (details in
1474: `research/e4-calibration-targets.md`). The central %-benchmark is an *output* the
1475: model computes, but mapping it to observed realized-to-appraised ratios is **not a
1476: direct overlay**: the two are different constructs (§6), so it is a **candidate
1477: validation target requiring an explicit construct bridge**, not a one-step
1478: calibration.
1479: 
1480: | Model quantity | Model value | Real-world proxy | Candidate dataset(s) | Status |
1481: |---|---|---|---|---|
1482: | central %-benchmark | 46–68% | realized ÷ appraised value | World Bank IEG ratings; Flyvbjerg megaproject DB | candidate target; needs an explicit construct mapping |
1483: | η (harm-blindness) | 0–0.5 | passive vs active waste share | Bandiera-Prat-Valletti 2009 (83% passive, setting-specific: Italian standardized-goods procurement) | anchored-direction |
1484: | β (voice inequality) | 0.2–0.5 | PB participation bias | NYC / Paris / Porto Alegre; Decidim / Consul | calibratable |
1485: | q, m (detection) | q ≈ 0.5–1%, m in hundreds | complaint / whistleblowing rates | FTC Consumer Sentinel; NYC 311; Dyck et al. 2010 | calibratable |
1486: | λ threshold | central ≈ 0.10 | procurement rents / bribe depth | Olken 2007; WB Enterprise Surveys | calibratable |
1487: | penalty f | equal both sides | legal sanction scale | held equal (conservative) | scope choice |
1488: 
1489: The v1.14 four-scenario map (§6) makes the same anchoring explicit for its harm-myopia model: the visibility long
1490: tail is source-motivated by heavy-tailed public procurement (Skuhrovec et al. 2013), participation by
1491: participatory-budgeting turnout, and the harm-detection gate by the agenda-setting/salience literature; the
1492: per-knob anchors and their strength are recorded in `research/e4-plausible-anchors.md`, with the reproducible
1493: scenarios, frontier, and theorem in `scripts/simulation/e4-v5/` and `research/e4-parity-theorem.md`.
