 755: 
 756: **Finding 4: aggregated dispersed signals outperform fixed-bandwidth
 757: central construction of the weight vector — but a fair, symmetric
 758: re-examination resolves the advantage into a conditional frontier and adds a
 759: capture-resistance that guards it.** A fourth, pre-registered experiment
 760: (design and predictions committed before any run;
 761: `research/e4-institutional-knowledge-design.md`) models knowledge
 762: symmetrically instead of endowing it: a planner with fixed bandwidth
 763: (thirty deep inspections; its correlation with latent quality is now
 764: measured output, collapsing 0.81 → 0.37 → 0.17 as the project pool grows
 765: 40 → 200 → 1000) against thirty percent of citizens holding four
 766: individually poor local signals each (noise 0.35). Five regimes share the
 767: identical world and signals and differ only in the aggregation
 768: institution. The pre-registered scale-crossover prediction failed in the
 769: informative direction: open construction of the weight vector — a plain
 770: average of citizen signals per project — beats pure central construction
 771: at *every* scale, including the smallest, where the planner inspects
 772: three-quarters of the world (sel(θ) 0.76 vs 0.62 at N = 40; 0.73 vs 0.04
 773: at N = 1000). Twelve thousand noisy signals average into a near-perfect
 774: vector; thirty good inspections cannot compete, and fixed central
 775: bandwidth decays toward randomness as the world grows — a Condorcet
 776: (1785) aggregation logic, and we treat it as such: the jury theorem's
 777: known failure conditions (Austen-Smith and Banks 1996) define exactly
 778: the boundary the seventh experiment tests. Three
 779: qualifications carry the finding's honest weight. First, the same
 780: dispersed knowledge *without* an aggregation institution is wasted: the
 781: uncoordinated regime funds 0.6–15% of projects and selects poorly — the
 782: result vindicates aggregation mechanisms, not the absence of mechanism,
 783: and Core v0's default-plus-closure layer is exactly such a mechanism.
 784: Second, aggregation defeats noise, not bias: signals are unbiased by
 785: construction, and a common-mode bias uncorrelated with quality
 786: (misinformation, expressive allocation) would not average out — only
 787: endogenous social-proof contamination was tested, and proved largely
 788: benign because visible funding progress is itself quality-correlated in a
 789: well-anchored system. Third, elicitation is non-strategic by assumption;
 790: in deployment, signal reporting becomes a gaming and clientelism surface,
 791: and the mechanics of open scope construction remain a gated design
 792: problem. Within those bounds, the finding points in a clear direction: the binding variable is not who holds the pen but how much
 793: dispersed information the scope-construction institution ingests.
 794: 
 795: The simulation also disciplines rhetoric — in both directions. Nothing in
 796: E1–E3 supports describing Core v0 allocation as "the wisdom of crowds":
 797: the honest description is *inspectable intermediation with a
 798: citizen-correctable default*, which the results show is both realistic and
 799: better than the salience-driven alternative that unstructured platforms
 800: converge to. And nothing in E1–E3 licenses the opposite reading — that
 801: central planning knowledge beats distributed knowledge — because they
 802: never modeled distributed knowledge; when E4 does, aggregation wins
 803: wherever its named preconditions hold. Both discourses lose their slogan;
 804: the design keeps its numbers.
 805: 
 806: *A fair, symmetric re-examination (E4-v4/v5).* This first-pass E4 gave the
 807: central a fixed inspection bandwidth and left citizen signals unbiased — two
 808: idealizations that, an adversarial review showed, tilt the comparison in the
 809: distributed arm's favor. A rebuilt model
 810: (`scripts/simulation/e4-v4-symmetric-frontier.mjs`,
 811: `research/e4-v4-symmetric-frontier-results.txt`, `research/e4-v5-capture-design.md`)
 812: gives *both* institutions a symmetric friction in perceiving true value,
 813: including harm: the central attenuates perceived harm by a coefficient η (0 =
 814: blind to diffuse harm, 1 = a fully accountable planner), while the distributed
 815: reads true valuations but the diffusely harmed under-participate at a rate β
 816: (voice inequality). The result is not a multiplier but a frontier with a
 817: closed-form parity locus (`research/e4-analytical-backbone.md`): both
 818: institutions are biased estimators of the same Samuelson value T = S⁺ − S⁻,
 819: ranking projects by S⁺ − θ·S⁻ with θ_C = η and θ_D = 1 − β, so the distributed
 820: dominates exactly when its coefficient is closer to the true harm-weight of one
 821: — i.e. **β < 1 − η**. The simulation confirms the law (parity on the
 822: anti-diagonal η + β = 1) and quantifies the delivered-value degradation off it
 823: (rough parity to ~1.8× as a **distributed-to-central ratio** across the plausible
 824: box — this is D/C, not a fraction of the full-information benchmark). The advantage
 825: is thus a property of *including the harmed*, not of aggregation per se; it reaches
 826: parity along the anti-diagonal β = 1 − η and turns into a central win below it
 827: (β > 1 − η) — which absorbs the participation-bias objection into the model's own
 828: β axis rather than leaving it external. Neither
 829: extreme is assumed: η is *swept*, not fixed, and a low but non-zero η is a
 830: defended regime, not a premise. The diffuse-harm literature (Bastiat's unseen
 831: costs; Olson's asymmetric organization on contested issues; Wilson's
 832: client-politics quadrant; Scott's legibility) describes *when* diffuse costs go
 833: unrepresented — each read at its proper scope, not as a claim of global
 834: blindness — while the opposing thesis that political competition disciplines the
 835: centre toward efficiency (Wittman 1989) holds weakest in exactly that
 836: client-politics quadrant. Empirically, most *measured* procurement loss is
 837: passive — incompetence, not theft (Bandiera, Prat and Valletti 2009) —
 838: consistent with a low but non-zero η.
 839: 
 840: *Capture-resistance guards the advantage (E4-v5).* Modelling organized capture
 841: symmetrically — the review's hardest objection, applied in fairness to the
 842: central planner too — the asymmetry widens rather than closes. A group captures
 843: a low-value project only when its private rent exceeds acquisition cost plus the
 844: expected sanction (Becker 1968); with the deterrence asymmetry carried entirely
 845: by detection probability and acquisition scaling (the penalty held equal,
 846: conservatively), the status quo turns net-harmful at rents near 10% of project
 847: cost while the distributed threshold — floored by the equal-per-citizen wallet,
 848: which money can persuade but cannot buy — sits roughly ten times higher (closed
 849: form ρ(C) in the backbone note). Detection is a snowball p = 1 − (1 − q)^m, so
 850: its floor is an expected m·q ≥ −ln(1 − p_c) ≈ 0.1 reporters drawn from the
 851: transparent affected public — low, but this is a model-internal statement whose
 852: force depends entirely on the stipulated detection gap (central ~0.10 vs
 853: distributed ~1.0), not an empirical burden-of-proof: sensitivity analysis is
 854: decisive here — the distributed advantage narrows and can reverse if distributed
 855: detection is driven down toward ~0.3, so the claim is that organized recapture is
 856: harder under the distributed arm's transparency *given these parameters*, not that
 857: it is ruled out. This ties Finding
 858: 4 to the integrity layer of Finding 5: the same fiscalization that makes value
 859: arrive is what keeps the allocation advantage from being bought back by
 860: organized rents, so the two are a layer and its safeguard rather than
 861: independent multipliers. Every magnitude here is model-internal; the literature
 862: (Olson, Wilson, Scott, Bastiat; Becker, Becker and Stigler, Stokes,
 863: Dyck-Morse-Zingales; Ostrom's self-monitoring commons) defends the direction,
 864: the mechanism, and the sign of the asymmetry — not the numbers.
 865: 
 866: *Analytical backbone.* Three closed forms carry the weight, each verified against
 867: the simulation (`research/e4-analytical-backbone.md`); the runs then only confirm
 868: them and quantify the degradation off the clean cases. **(i) The parity law.**
 869: Writing each institution as a biased estimator that ranks projects by S⁺ − θ·S⁻,
 870: the central keeps θ_C = η of perceived harm and the distributed reveals
 871: θ_D = 1 − β (the participation rate cancels from the ranking); since the true
 872: harm-weight is one, the distributed arm delivers more true value **iff
 873: β < 1 − η**, parity on the anti-diagonal. A bias–variance reading would predict
 874: that on the parity line, where the bias cancels, the lower-variance estimator wins —
 875: the distributed's revelation noise is zero (a funder knows her own value), the
 876: central's proxy noise is not. The implemented simulation does **not** bear this out
 877: at the accountable corner: at (η = 1, β = 0) the measured ratio is **0.89× — a
 878: central win (D/C < 1)** — so the honest reading is the noise-free parity law
 879: β = 1 − η, and the bias–variance tilt toward the distributed is not supported there.
 880: **(ii) The capture
 881: threshold.** From rent > acquisition + P(detect)·penalty, the central's threshold
 882: λ\*_C = (k_c + p_c·f)/C falls toward zero as its detection shrinks, while the
 883: distributed's λ\*_D = k_d + p_d·f/C is *floored* by the equal-wallet acquisition
 884: term k_d; the resistance ratio ρ(C) = (k_d·C + p_d·f)/(k_c + p_c·f) ≈ 6–10×,
 885: rising in project cost. **(iii) The detection floor.** With snowball detection
 886: P = 1 − (1 − q)^m, beating a central rate p_c needs, in the small-*q* (Poisson)
 887: approximation (1 − q)^m ≈ e^{−m·q}, only an expected m·q ≥ −ln(1 − p_c) ≈ 0.1
 888: reporters — the exact Bernoulli condition is m ≥ ln(1 − p_c)/ln(1 − q), which
 889: depends on *m* and *q* separately, not only on their product. It is a
 890: model-internal detection floor under the stipulated parameters
 891: (sensitivity-dependent; see Finding 4), not an empirical burden-of-proof inversion.
 892: Three invariances bound the arbitrary-magnitudes worry — as properties of the
 893: noise-free, large-set *expectation*, not of every finite-sample run: the advantage
 894: is invariant to the units of value (scale); in expectation it depends on the
 895: voice-bias β rather than on the participation *level* (though in finite samples
 896: turnout changes sample size, sampling variance, and hence rankings and
 897: portfolios); and, because only the first moments S⁺, S⁻ enter the expected
 898: ranking, the Gaussian valuation draw is a convenience there rather than a
 899: load-bearing assumption (finite-sample tails and valuation shape can still move
 900: rankings). One honest boundary the runs mark: the parity law is the large-set
 901: limit; when a project's interested set is very small — a handful of people — the
 902: distributed's sampling variance dominates and a full-census central regains the
 903: edge. Two further boundaries are honest to state. The comparison is *static* — a
 904: single allocation round — whereas real harms surface over iterated cycles and
 905: feed back through elections and audit, so a persistently blind centre is the
 906: stress case, not an inevitability. And the distributed arm is *scored on the true
 907: value it reveals*, which would be circular were it not that the β voice-bias and
 908: the capture frictions make its revealed signal a biased, contestable estimate of
 909: that value rather than a definitional one.
