FILE drafts/paper.md 1270-1320
1270: conducted entirely outside the system — are made harder and more
1271: discoverable, never impossible; the architecture's claims are comparative
1272: (against opaque monopoly), not absolute.
1273: 
1274: **Meta-governance in open mode is deferred by design.** Rule-change
1275: procedure, versioning, and non-surprise constraints are specified; the
1276: constitutional mechanics — rules for making rules (Buchanan and Tullock
1277: 1962) — of who votes on protocol changes in a mature
1278: open-mode deployment are deliberately not. Open-mode deployment is gated on
1279: resolving them.
1280: 
1281: **Adoption selects, and the thesis does not depend on it.** This paper
1282: addresses whether the architecture can be built and how its *selection*
1283: mechanism behaves under a symmetric, delivery-at-parity test — not whether it
1284: delivers more value in the world (a total delivered-value effect is a separately
1285: identified future estimand, not claimed here), and not whether any authority
1286: wants it. The corpus supplies the
1287: deployment layer for an authority that has decided (prospective
1288: baselines measured from instrumentation onset, credit attribution on
1289: verified delivery, institutional rather than personal timeout attribution
1290: in the first cycle, and a symmetry clause barring any operator from
1291: exempting its own projects), and names the plausible adopter archetypes —
1292: the post-scandal challenger, the mandating higher government, the
1293: conditioned external funder. The honest selection effect stands: the
1294: architecture will plausibly be adopted first by relatively clean or newly
1295: arrived sponsors, in the places that need it least.
1296: 
1297: **The outcome measure is a bounded, non-distributional aggregate.** The value
1298: the model scores is a cardinal utilitarian-style sum over affected parties on a
1299: bounded, infrastructure-like public-investment slice; it is not distributionally
1300: weighted and says nothing about redistribution, equity, or who bears benefits and
1301: harms. A portfolio can score well on this measure while distributing badly.
1302: Applying the criterion across groups, or to the whole budget or the purpose of
1303: taxation, would require a separate social-welfare and incidence specification this
1304: paper does not provide. The model is also partial-equilibrium: strategic
1305: reporting, endogenous proposal supply, project complementarities, tax incidence,
1306: and general-equilibrium effects are outside it (see the
1307: [claim-and-estimand-contract](../research/claim-and-estimand-contract.md)).
1308: 
1309: **Epistemically, this is one team's self-critiqued design.** The
1310: adversarial corpus was produced by the same research effort it attacks,
1311: with AI assistance; the earlier apparatus's status-quo baseline was
1312: audit-parameterized (its parameters drawn item-by-item from published
1313: audit-institution findings, with primary-source verification still in progress), while the current symmetry gate is an uncalibrated
1314: stylized selection test — neither is calibrated to a specific PB dataset,
1315: and the remaining parameters are plausible rather than measured; and no
1316: pilot has been run. The three missing validations — independent expert
1317: attack, calibration to empirical PB data, and a bounded tutored pilot
1318: (sports-sector, one municipality) — are the research program's next
1319: phase, in that order.
